# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1972-minnesota-twins-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-washington-senators-season] The 1901 Washington Senators won 61 games, lost 72, and finished in sixth place in the American League in its first year as a major league team.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1901-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jim Manning and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1902-washington-senators-season] The **1902 Washington Senators** won 61 games, lost 75, and finished in sixth place in the American League.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1902-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Tom Loftus and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The **1903 Washington Senators** won 43 games, lost 94, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Washington had finished in sixth place in each of the previous two seasons (the first two seasons of the American League's existence).
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1903-washington-senators-season] However, they fell to eighth and last in 1903.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their only star player, Big Ed Delahanty, got drunk and fell off a bridge into Niagara Falls midway through the season.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The Senators' pitching had always been bad, and indeed, they would allow the most runs in the AL, but without Delahanty the offense sputtered to a halt.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their collective batting average was .231, bad even for the dead-ball era, and no one drove in more than 49 runs.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1904-washington-senators-season] The **1904 Washington Senators** won 38 games, lost 113, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1904-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Malachi Kittridge and Patsy Donovan and played home games at National Park.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1904-washington-senators-season] Their winning percentage of .252 is fourth worst for any MLB team since 1900.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1905-washington-senators-season] The **1905 Washington Senators** won 64 games, lost 87, and finished in seventh place in the American League.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1905-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jake Stahl and played home games at National Park.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1906-washington-senators-season] The **1906 Washington Senators** won 55 games, lost 95, and finished in seventh place in the American League.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1906-washington-senators-season] Shortstop Joe Cassidy died in March 1906 due to complications from typhoid and malaria.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1906-washington-senators-season] The Senators opened their 1906 season against the Philadelphia Athletics at Columbia Park in Philadelphia.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] The **1972 Minnesota Twins season**was the 12th season for the Minnesota Twins franchise in the Twin Cities of Minnesota, their 12th season at Metropolitan Stadium and the 72nd overall in the American League.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] The Twins finished 77–77, third in the American League West.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] On May 12, in a twenty-two inning match which concluded a day later, Danny Thompson went 0 for 10 with a sacrifice bunt, dropping his batting average 39 points over one game.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] He and César Tovar set a team record with their eleven plate appearances.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] After a slow start, manager Bill Rigney was replaced by Frank Quilici in early July.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] On July 9, Rich Reese hit his third pinch-hit grand slam home run, tying a major league record in doing so.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Rothsay, Minnesota, native Dave Goltz made his major league debut on July 18 – he is the first Minnesotan drafted by the Minnesota Twins to make the big league club.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Only one Twin made the All-Star Game: second baseman Rod Carew.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] On July 31, pitcher Bert Blyleven gave up two inside-the-park home runs, both to the Chicago White Sox Dick Allen.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] When this next occurs in the major leagues (October 4, 1986), Blyleven is again on the mound.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] But the feat is accomplished this time by his Minnesota teammate Greg Gagne.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] When César Tovar hit for the cycle on September 19, he finished with a game-ending home run.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] The only other player to do that in history was Ken Boyer (1961).
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] In later years, and after such a hit became known as a "walk-off home run", the feat was duplicated by George Brett (1979), Dwight Evans (1984), and Carlos González (2010).
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Tovar is just the second Twin to hit for the cycle, after Rod Carew in 1970; eight more Twins will do so by 2009.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Carew won his second AL batting title with a .318 average, but did not hit any home runs during the season.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Previously, Zach Wheat was the last player to accomplish this feat when he won the 1918 NL batting title with the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Bobby Darwin showed potential as a hitter with 22 HR and 80 RBI, but that did not make up for age and injuries taking their toll on other players.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] (Those numbers were also suppressed by his Twins-record 145 strikeouts.) Harmon Killebrew hit 26 HR (4th in the league) but drove in only 75 runs.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Tony Oliva's bad knees limited him to only 10 games.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] César Tovar led the team with 86 runs scored.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Four pitchers had double digit wins: Bert Blyleven (17–17), Dick Woodson (14–14), Jim Perry (13–16), and Jim Kaat (10–2).
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] Kaat also won his 11th Gold Glove Award.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] 797,901 fans attended Twins games, the seventh highest total in the American League.
[src:1972-minnesota-twins-season/1972-minnesota-twins-season] It was almost half the number of fans that had attended just a few seasons earlier.
